loc: Osaka Castle Park, Chuo-ku, Osaka City, Osaka Prefecture
rmk:
Male individual on passage (stayed on May 3 and 4) in a famous urban
stopover (Osaka Castle Park) of (mainly) land birds.  Recorded in a crowd of
birdwatchers and photographers.  Human voice has been somewhat
suppressed by high-pass filtering.  Both songs and calls were recorded.
This individual had unusual songs comprising of song elements
of both Ficedula mugimaki and Ficedula narcissina.
The initial two phrases are typical songs of Ficedula mugimaki.
The phrase starting at 0:30 is typical of Ficedula narcissina
(also phrases at 0:36, 0:39-0:41s and 1:11s are those of 
Ficedula narcissina).
The phrase at 1:05-1:07s is typical one of Ficedula narcissina
(often referred to the sound of cicada Meimuna opalifera
among Japanese birdwatchers).  Although this individual
mimics song elements of Ficedula narcissina, the ending of
the phrase is characteristic of Ficedula mugimaki.
Recording made using LG Optimus smartphone.  An immature Mugimaki flycatcher was observed and recording along a mountain ridge at the northeast of the island.

rmk:
Suspected ID of the soft call.  The voice was from the bird which was actively moving.
There were also narcissus flycatchers, but the sounds were lower than
those of the narcissus flycatcher.  Potential confusion species might be
a background thrush.  The intervals between notes do not reflect
true ones since I removed noisy parts.  The actual notes were usually
a pair or a single one (not clustered), which is typical for Ficedula.
